In computer science and s= oftware engineering research, concepts such as modular design, continuous i= ntegration, and deprecation policies are second nature; they are taught as = part of the discipline. As a result, code written for histo= rical research may be more prone to issues that hinder longevity (hard-code= d file paths, poor error handling, lack of tests). When comparing code qual= ity analyses, one study found that research software in engineering fields = tended to have better documentation and version control use than a sample o= f humanities research software, reflecting this training gaphowisonlab.github.ioacademic.oup.com= . Initiatives like Software Carpentry and libr= ary-led digital scholarship workshops are attempting to bridge this gap by = teaching humanities researchers skills in sustainable coding and project ma= nagement. Over time, as these practices diffuse, we may see fewer differenc= es in sustainability outcomes between disciplines. Another comparative point is the= role of commercial vs. aca= demic support. In some scientific domains with industry ties (e.g.= , medical imaging, climate modeling), software started in academia may late= r receive commercial backing or find a home in an institutional facility th= at ensures long-term support (like national labs). For example, ESRI=E2=80=99s ArcGIS, while not a research proje= ct per se, is heavily used in archaeology; its longevity is assured by a co= mpany through a paid model, whereas QGIS (open-source alternative) relies on volunteer developers wor= ldwide. Interestingly, QGIS has managed to sustain rapid development for ov= er 20 years, demonstrating that open-source models can match or exceed commercial longevity if a crit= ical mass of contributors and users is reached. Few humanities tools have t= hat critical mass, but one that does is Pandoc (a universal document converter widely used for scho= larly writing, including digital humanities). Pandoc, created by a single a= cademic initially, grew to have many contributors and is now backed by gran= ts. On the other h= and, insights from commercial software practices, such as end-of-life (EOL) planning, could i= nform academic projects. Companies typically announce well in advance when = support for a version will end and provide migration paths (e.g., data expo= rt or conversion tools for the next version). Rarely do academic projects a= rticulate an EOL plan. An instructive contrast is the policy of the UK Data Service: when dec= ommissioning an old data interface, they preserved the data in standard for= mats and provided users with new tools. Research software projects in histo= ry could similarly plan for handover =E2=80=93 for instance, by ensuring th= at when a project=E2=80=99s website eventually goes offline, its code and d= ocumentation are deposited in a library or repository for posterity.

It=E2=80=99s also worth comparin= g the scale of resources involved. Big science projects (like the Large Hadron Collider exper= iments or space missions) often treat software as mission-critical, dedicat= ing whole teams to its upkeep, because a failure of software might jeopardi= ze the scientific mission. In such contexts, rigorous testing, documentatio= n, and redundancy are non-negotiable. Historical research projects rarely h= ave such high stakes or budgets; thus, the level of formal process applied = is typically lower. However, some large-scale humanities infrastructures, l= ike Europeana (a platform = aggregating cultural heritage data), have begun to adopt engineering approa= ches akin to big science. Europeana=E2=80=99s platform software undergoes c= ontinuous development with professional IT staff, and they actively address= sustainability through periodic refactoring and cloud deployment to keep t= he system modern. This industrial approach is more the exception than the r= ule in humanities, but it shows the potential when resources permit. In sum= , while the fundamental challenges of sustaining research software are wide= ly shared, historical studies can learn from other fields by embracing community governance, integrati= ng software engineering best practices, and planning for obsolescence in a = structured way. Conversely, the humanities=E2=80=99 experience wit= h digital preservation (an area where libraries and archives have robust frameworks) is somet= hing scientific software efforts can learn from =E2=80=93 for example, the = use of format migration and emulation strategies long practiced in preservi= ng digital artifacts could be applied to preserving executability of scient= ific codes. Cross-domain dialogues, often facilitated by initiatives like t= he Research Software Alliance and the interdisciplinary WSSSPE workshops, a= re helping to transfer such insights across disciplinary boundaries.

Finally, considering commercial software literature: while= academia cannot replicate commercial funding streams, certain principles a= re transferable. User-cente= red design and ite= rative development (common in industry via agile methodologies) ca= n result in software that continues to be used and thus justified to mainta= in. Academic projects often start with a tight focus on research requiremen= ts, but by engaging users (e.g., other scholars, students, citizen scientis= ts) and iterating, they may broaden the tool=E2=80=99s appeal and longevity= . Moreover, companies often maintain backward compatibility =E2=80=93 an et= hic that could be valuable in research software (ensuring, for instance, th= at a corpus analysis tool can still read data produced by its 10-year-old v= ersion). In practice, there is sometimes a trade-off between innovation and= backward compatibility, but an awareness of not stranding users on older d= ata formats can guide design choices. In summary, commercial best practices like managed deprecation, = user support, and roadmapping could beneficially inform academic s= oftware maintenance, even if the scale differs. Conversely, the academic em= phasis on openness and community may increasingly influence commercial enti= ties (for example, open-core models and community editions of software), il= lustrating a bidirectional exchange of ideas on sustainability.

5. Identification of Gaps and F= uture Directions

Despite growing awareness, signi= ficant gaps remain= in the literature and practice of research software sustainability, especi= ally in historical studies. One glaring gap is the limited empirical data specific to humanities softw= are lifecycles. While studies in other fields have quantified code= availability and longevitydiw.dejasss.org, we lack a comprehensive survey or longit= udinal study focusing on, say, digital history or archaeology software. The= reasons are manifold: humanities projects are numerous but dispersed, and = many are not captured in public repositories or indices (making them harder= to sample). There is also a cultural gap =E2=80=93 historically, humanitie= s computing did not prioritize formal evaluation of tools in the way that s= ciences did for reproducibility. This gap in data hampers our ability to ge= neralize: Are the lifespans of humanities research software indeed shorter = on average than those in science? Do particular subfields (like corpus ling= uistics) outperform others (like digital history) in sustaining tools? Anec= dotal evidence suggests many tools don=E2=80=99t survive more than a few ye= ars without updates, but solid data would help confirm, challenge, or nuanc= e this view. Future research should leverage methods like web scraping and archival retrieval to comp= ile inventories of past projects (for example, mining conference proceeding= s and project databases for mentions of software) and then checking their c= urrent status. Such a study would provide a baseline =E2=80=9Csurvival rate= =E2=80=9D for historical research software and identify common factors in t= he survivors.

Another gap lies in the methodologies for tracking software= impact and use over time. In traditional scholarship, citations s= erve as a proxy for impact and can be tracked via bibliometrics; for softwa= re, citation practices are inconsistent at best. Many humanities publicatio= ns do not formally cite the software they use, or they might mention it in = passing (making it hard for citation indices to catch). This means we might= be undercounting the continued use of older software, leading to premature= assumptions of obsolescence. Developing better metrics and indexing for so= ftware usage is a priority. One approach is encouraging journals to require= software citations in references (an effort championed by groups like FORCE11 and the Softwa= re Citation Principles). If historical journals and monographs systematical= ly listed software references (with DOIs or URLs), bibliometric databases c= ould start capturing this data. In turn, it would become possible to see, f= or example, that a tool like MALLET (a topic modeling software from 2002) i= s still being cited in 2025, indicating ongoing use. Without such data, it = is difficult to know when a piece of software truly =E2=80=9Cdies=E2=80=9D = in the scholarly community. Infrastructure for usage analytics (like the download stats provi= ded by PyPI or npm for packages) is also lacking for many bespoke tools. Re= positories like Zenodo can track downloads of archived software packages, w= hich is helpful, but only if projects deposit their code there (still not a= universal practice). A future direction is to create a central index of humanities research software= with persistent IDs, wherein projects register their tools and ca= n be periodically pinged or checked. This could function akin to a catalogu= e raisonn=C3=A9 of digital humanities tools, assisting both in discovery an= d in lifecycle tracking. The recently founded Critical Digital Infrastructure initiative by s= ome funding bodies (e.g., the Mellon Foundation) hints at moving this direc= tion by cataloguing and supporting key scholarly software.

There are also gaps in guidance and policy. While = frameworks like FAIR, as discussed, exist, many historical researchers rema= in unaware of them or unsure how to implement them for software. Unlike dat= a management (which now is often supported by institutional data services),= software management planning is still ad hoc. University libraries and dig= ital scholarship centers could play a stronger role in bridging this gap. F= or instance, a library might offer a =E2=80=9Cresearch software sustainabil= ity consultation=E2=80=9D similar to data management consultations. However= , to do so, they need a clear set of best practices to draw upon, tailored = to humanities contexts. Currently, much of the sustainability literature is= general or science-oriented; translating that into field-specific guidelines is a to-do item= . What does =E2=80=9Cinteroperability=E2=80=9D mean for a historical lingui= stics tool in practice? Perhaps ensuring it uses Unicode and standard lingu= istic annotations. What does a good =E2=80=9Cmaintenance plan=E2=80=9D look= like for an archaeology database? Perhaps a commitment that the data will = be exportable to CSV or SQL and that the code will be released under an ope= n license with basic documentation at project end. These specifics need to = be worked out and disseminated. A promising development is the emergence of= research software engineer= s (RSEs) in the humanities. The RSE movement, which started in the= UK and has spread internationally, explicitly addresses the human resource= gap by creating roles for people who specialize in research software devel= opment within academia. Historically, humanities departments rarely had sta= ff dedicated to software; this is slowly changing with digital humanities l= abs hiring RSE-type positions. Over the next decade, this could significant= ly improve continuity and institutional memory for software projects =E2=80= =93 but only if funding models adapt to support such roles beyond short-ter= m grants.

In terms of future research directions, several = stand out:

  • Lifecycle Models for Humanities Software: Developi= ng conceptual models that describe typical stages of a tool (from initial p= rototype to mature tool to legacy/archive stage) in humanities contexts. Su= ch models can inform when and how to allocate resources. For example, a mod= el might suggest that after 5 years of no updates, a software project shoul= d be transitioned to a =E2=80=9Clegacy preservation=E2=80=9D stage (packagi= ng the final version for archival, writing a summary of its status, etc.). = Defining these stages and triggers for action can ensure projects don=E2=80= =99t simply languish silently.

  • Economic and Incentive Studies: We need a better u= nderstanding of the economics of sustaining research software. What would i= t actually cost to keep a given tool running and supported? Some work has t= ried to estimate the monetary value of volunteer contributions in open-sour= ce science software, but similar analyses could be done for humanities proj= ects to make the case to funders that, say, an annual investment of $X coul= d keep widely used tool Y operational. Coupled with this, exploring incenti= ve mechanisms =E2=80=93 could we create academic credit for maintenance (e.= g., via publications like =E2=80=9Csoftware update=E2=80=9D papers or an in= dex that tracks software contributions in hiring committees)? These are soc= iological questions that require gathering data from academic hiring, promo= tion, and funding processes.

  • Technical Preservation Strategies: On the technica= l side, research into conta= inerization, virtualization, and emulation for preservation is hig= hly relevant. One future direction is the idea of preserving entire computational environments. Proje= cts like Software Heritage<= /strong> are already archiving source code from across the webdanielskatz.org, but running that code in the future may require cap= turing the environment. Tools like Docker and VMware can snapshot environme= nts now; the challenge is ensuring those snapshots remain usable 10+ years = on. There is ongoing research in the digital preservation community on emul= ation-as-a-service, which could be extended to scholarly software (for inst= ance, an archived virtual machine that runs a 2010 archaeological visualiza= tion tool on a legacy OS could be spun up on demand in the cloud in 2030). = Humanities researchers should engage with this line of work, perhaps by col= laborating with computer scientists in preservation or adopting these metho= ds for key resources. A concrete step would be for conferences like Digital Humanities or Computer Applications in Archaeology (CAA)= to introduce tracks on software sustainability where such cross-cutti= ng technical solutions are discussed.

  • Community Building and Knowledge Exchange: Lastly,= a softer but crucial direction is fostering a culture of knowledge exchange about sustainability. Ri= ght now, a historian grappling with how to extend the life of a mapping too= l may not be aware of similar efforts by an ecologist or an astronomer, yet= they share the problem. Interdisciplinary forums (publications, workshops)= dedicated to research software sustainability can bridge this gap. The Journal of Open Source Software (J= OSS) and Journal of Open R= esearch Software (JORS) are great venues that have begun publishing ar= ticles on software from all fields, including some humanities projects. Enc= ouraging more historical software authors to publish in these journals (whi= ch requires cleaning and documenting the code) will not only improve the so= ftware itself but also contribute to an evidence base of what works and wha= t doesn=E2=80=99t.

In identifying these gaps, it be= comes clear that addressing them will require both top-down interventions (policies, funding prioritie= s) and bottom-up e= fforts (community best practices, individual projects serving as exemplars)= . The future of historical research software sustainability lies i= n normalizing the idea that software is an integral scholarly product =E2= =80=93 one that merits preservation akin to an article or a monograph. As t= hat idea takes hold, we can expect to see more robust support structures: p= erhaps digital humanities centers acting as long-term stewards for software= the way libraries steward publications, or consortia of historians pooling= resources to maintain crucial tools (as is already happening in some corne= rs, e.g., the maintainers of the International Historical GIS data have formed a consortium to ensure= the software and data remain available). The ultimate vision is that schol= ars in 50 years will still be able to access and run (or at least examine) = the software that underpinned today=E2=80=99s research, thus fully unlockin= g the reproducibility and reuse of scholarly knowledge.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the longevity, li= fecycle, and sustainability of research software in historical studies pres= ent a complex challenge that intertwines technical, social, and organizatio= nal factors. Our review has shown that while the awareness of the issue is growing, with fram= eworks like FAIR4RS and initiatives from the Research Software Engineer mov= ement beginning to take root, there is still a considerable journey ahead t= o embed sustainable practices in the DNA of historical scholarship. Key the= mes that emerge include the need for proactive planning =E2=80=93 treating software maintena= nce and end-of-life considerations as first-class concerns in project desig= n =E2=80=93 and the importance of community and institutional support in sustaining software = beyond the efforts of individual creators. Historical studies, in engaging = with these issues, are increasingly learning from parallel efforts in the s= ciences and industry, adopting best practices such as open source collabora= tion, containerization, and continuous integration, albeit slowly and uneve= nly. At the same time, the domain-specific context of humanities projects (= often smaller scale, with unique data and fewer developers) means solutions= must be tailored and pragmatic.

One actionable insight is the cr= itical role of interoperabi= lity and data portability as a hedge against software obsolescence= : by using standard data formats and open APIs, historical research softwar= e can ensure that even if the original tool ceases development, the data an= d research results can be taken forward into new platformsatsf.co.ukpermacomputing.net. This approach shifts the focus from = preserving a particular tool to preserving the work done with that tool. Another insight is that sust= ainability is as much a human challenge as a technical one =E2=80=93 recogn= izing and rewarding the labor of software maintenance, and building multi-g= enerational teams where outgoing developers train newcomers, can greatly ex= tend a project=E2=80=99s life. The review also highlights promising develop= ments, such as journals beginning to accept software submissions and specia= l issues on digital infrastructure, which create scholarly credit for softw= are products. Such recognition is vital to incentivize academics to invest = time in robust, well-documented, long-lived software.

Looking forward, as historical d= isciplines continue to digitize and computational methods become ever more = central, the stakes for software sustainability will only increase. Without= concerted effort, we risk a =E2=80=9Cdigital dark age=E2=80=9D for scholar= ship where important analyses cannot be replicated or built upon because th= e tools vanished. Conversely, by closing the identified gaps =E2=80=93 thro= ugh better empirical understanding, cross-domain learning, and dedicated in= frastructure =E2=80=93 we can move toward an ecosystem in which research so= ftware in history and related fields is as enduring and accessible as the p= rimary sources scholars curate. Future research should focus on implementing the recommendati= ons discussed and studying their efficacy: for example, piloting mandatory = software management plans in grant programs and tracking outcomes, or estab= lishing a collaborative maintenance hub for a set of widely used humanities= tools and observing usage over time. Such experiments, duly reported, will= enrich the literature with practical models for others to emulate. In esse= nce, achieving sustainability for historical research software is an ongoin= g process of cultural change and technical adaptation, one that must be con= tinually assessed and refined. This literature review, by bringing together= knowledge from diverse domains, aims to lay a foundation for that process,= enabling historians and their collaborators to approach software developme= nt not as a transient side-task, but as an integral and enduring component = of scholarly practice.

3. Empirical Evidence and Case = Studies

Methodological Reflections: The empirical studies = to date employ various methodologies =E2=80=93 surveys, repository mining, = case study, and archival analysis =E2=80=93 each with limitations. Surveys (like the Endings project= =E2=80=99s or the UK SSI=E2=80=99s surveys of researchers) provide breadth = but rely on self-report and perceptions of sustainability; they might not a= lways capture the technical reality of whether software is truly preservabl= e. Repository mining yield= s quantitative measures of activity and preservation (commits, releases, ar= chived copies) but can miss context (e.g. a quiet repository might still be= widely used in its frozen form, or a flurry of commits might not equate to= useful evolution). Case studie= s and post-mortems give rich detail on specific projects, though with = the caveat that each project has unique circumstances (so generalizing from= one case can be risky). Notably, Howison and Herbsleb (2011) advocated for= analyzing software sustainability via the concept of software ecosystems and use-contextsjames.howison.namejames.howison.n= ame. They reconstructed the dependen= cy network of scientific software components in several research fields and= found that software which became embedded in multiple =E2=80=9Cuse-context= s=E2=80=9D (different research projects, different user communities) tended= to have longer viabilityjames.= howison.namejames.howison.name. This suggests an empirical indicator: software wit= h more users and uses surv= ives longer. In historical studies, one might test this by looking at, say,= text analysis tools that crossed over from one project to many (such as Vo= yant Tools, a textual analysis web app widely reused). Indeed, Voyant =E2= =80=93 developed around 2010 =E2=80=93 is still in use today and has an act= ive maintenance cycle, likely because it garnered a broad user base in digi= tal humanities teaching and research, illustrating Howison=E2=80=99s point.=

The limitations of empirical wor= k in this area also highlight future needs. There is, for example, a lack of longitudinal tracking =E2=80=93 few studies follow a cohort of software projects over a dec= ade to see exactly when and how they break or thrive. Additionally, current= empirical studies often focus on either the technical artifacts (code, websites) or the social aspects (surveys of developers)= but rarely both in tandem. A mixed-method longitudinal study, combining re= pository data, user surveys, and developer interviews for a set of historic= al research software, would significantly enrich understanding of software = lifecycles. As of now, the scholarly literature provides strong hints and i= solated metrics =E2=80=93 such as =E2=80=9Chalf-life of code=E2=80=9D analo= gies to datadigitalhumaniti= es.org =E2=80=93 but a comprehensive= empirical model for software longevity is still in development.

4. Comparative Analysis

Approaches in Historical Studies vs. Scientific Fields: The strategies employed to achieve software sustainability can differ= considerably between historical studies and other disciplines, owing to di= fferent cultures and project scales. In historical studies and digital humanities, sustainabi= lity approaches have often been project-centric. Each project (say a digital edition of letters or a = history GIS application) might develop its own ad hoc strategy for wrapping= up =E2=80=93 for example, publishing a final book or DVD, depositing mater= ials in a library, or just keeping a website running as long as someone pay= s the hosting. The Endings project is an attempt to systematize this for hu= manities by providing a common approach (focusing on data longevity and sta= tic outputs)dh-tech.github.io= ideah.pubpub.org. Likewise, libraries have taken a lead in deve= loping preservation strategies specifically for humanities projects, as see= n in Goddard=E2=80=99s six approaches (dark archive, repository, etc.) desi= gned with DH content in mindideah.= pubpub.org= ideah.pubpub.org<= /a>. By contrast, in the natural sciences and engineering, sustainability is of= ten approached at the infra= structure and community level. Large scientific software (for exam= ple, the CMS experiment sof= tware at CERN or the community climate models) is maintained through consortiums and= formal governance. These projects have roadmaps that extend over decades, = and responsibility is handed off systematically as personnel change. Best p= ractices from software engineering =E2=80=93 such as rigorous testing, cont= inuous integration, modular design =E2=80=93 are typically ingrained in the= se communities, which helps longevity by making software easier to update o= r port to new systems. Empirical software engineering research confirms tha= t scientific projects that adopt such practices tend to experience fewer br= eakages when environments changearxiv.orgarxiv.org. In fields like bioinformatics and astronomy, open-source communities have forme= d around key tools (e.g. the AstroPy library in astrophysics, or QGIS in ar= chaeology as an open alternative to commercial GIS). These communities abso= rb the maintenance load that would overwhelm any single research team. In h= istorical studies, true community-developed software is rarer (though not a= bsent =E2=80=93 the programming historian community or open-source OCR tool= s for historical texts are examples). The more typical scenario is a single= -team developed tool that might later be handed to a library or open-source= d in hope of attracting volunteers. The difference is one of bottom-up vs. top-down sustainability: sciences often plan sustainability up front as part of large collaborations (top-down: allocat= e roles for documentation, have an official repository, schedule for deprec= ation of old versions, etc.), whereas humanities projects often retrofit or= hand off their outputs at the = end of the project (bottom-up: hoping an interested library or individ= ual picks it up). This is gradually changing as digital humanities projects= become more collaborative and as agencies demand sustainability plans in p= roposals. For instance, the NEH=E2=80=99s Office of Digital Humanities now = asks applicants to address how their project=E2=80=99s data and tools will = be preserved or reused beyond the grant period, pushing humanities projects= closer to the planning style of the sciences.

Methodological Differences: Another point of compa= rison is methodology: the softw= are development methodologies used can influence sustainability. Scien= tific software groups, particularly those with engineering influence, are m= ore likely to use formal methodologies such as Agile development, with issue tracking, iterat= ive releases, and user feedback loops= researchgate.net<= /span>= carver.cs.ua.edu<= /a>. Humanities software development historically was more in= formal =E2=80=93 closer to a =E2=80=9Cskunkworks=E2=80=9D model or small-sc= ale artisanal development (often by scholar-programmers juggling multiple r= oles). Case studies in Easterbrook & Johns (2009) and Carver et al. (2007) highlight how computat= ional scientists tended to eschew heavyweight processes but still benefitte= d from some structured practices (like configuration management)researchgate.netoro.open.ac.uk. In recent years,= many digital humanities labs have professionalized their development, adop= ting version control, code review, and project management tools similar to = those in science labsideas-productivity.orgideas-productivity.org. The =E2=80=9C= two cultures=E2=80=9D observation (scientists vs. software enginee= rs) by Sletholt et al. (20= 12) noted that scientists value quick results and incremental prototyping, = sometimes at the expense of maintainability, whereas professional software = engineers value design and maintainability, sometimes at the expense of qui= ck resultsoro.open.ac.uk. Digital humanists= , who often come from the scholar side, historically followed the scientist= pattern (prototyping first, figuring out sustainability later). Now, with = more interplay between humanities and IT departments, one sees hybrid appro= aches: e.g., a digital history project might have an initial exploratory ph= ase (scholar-driven hacking to validate methods) followed by a refactoring = phase where an RSE or a hired developer re-engineers the prototype into a m= ore sustainable form. This two-phase model is explicitly recommended in som= e frameworks (SSI guides mention =E2=80=9Cbuild throwaway prototypes, then rebuild for longevity=E2=80=9D<= /em> as a tacticideas-productivity.org).

Borrowing Best Practices: Humanities projects have= begun to borrow best pract= ices from scientific and engineering fields to improve sustainabil= ity. A clear example is the uptake of automated testing and continuous integration (CI). Whil= e a typical digital history project a decade ago might not have any automat= ed tests, today projects like the Pelagios historical geography tools or the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI) processing software= use CI services to run test suites whenever code is updated, ensuring that= new changes don=E2=80=99t break existing functionality. This is directly b= orrowed from software engineering and contributes to longevity by catching = bugs early and documenting expected behavior (tests often serve as partial = documentation). Another best practice is containerization: packaging the software environment= using Docker or similar tools. In the sciences, containerization has becom= e important for reproducibility and for running legacy code on new machines= . In the humanities, we now see projects distributing Docker images or virt= ual machine images that encapsulate their software. For example, the SCIEDIPity platform for digital epigr= aphy provides a Docker image so that any future scholar can launch the= system with all dependencies, even if those dependencies (specific version= s of MySQL, PHP, etc.) become hard to find later. This reflects an adaptati= on of a commercial/industrial strategy (using virtual environments to handl= e deployment) to academic preservation needs. Modularity and use of standard libraries is ano= ther cross-pollinated practice: rather than writing a custom XML parser or = database engine, projects are encouraged to use well-established open-sourc= e libraries. This not only saves development time but ensures that if the p= roject=E2=80=99s original code languishes, the parts built on widely used l= ibraries can potentially be upgraded by others (since many projects share t= he same libraries). In essence, aligning with external standards and commun= ities (whether that=E2=80=99s a programming framework or a metadata standar= d) ties a project=E2=80=99s fate to a larger ecosystem rather than leaving = it isolated.

Commercial vs Academic Strategies: The question of= applying commercial software l= ongevity strategies to academic research software is intriguing. Comme= rcial software companies typically ensure longevity through mechanisms like= long-term support (LTS) ve= rsions, backward c= ompatibility, and = user support contracts. For example, Microsoft will support an ope= rating system for 10+ years with security patches; Oracle offers extended s= upport for old versions of its database for clients who need stability. Aca= demic projects obviously lack the financial incentives and resources to do = this at the same scale, but some analogous strategies are being tried. One = approach is creating LTS-li= ke releases of research software. The astrophysics community, for = instance, periodically declares certain versions of their code as =E2=80=9C= long-term stable=E2=80=9D and encourages users to stick with those for miss= ion-critical work, while development continues on a separate track. A digit= al humanities project could similarly issue a final stable version at proje= ct end (with thorough documentation and maybe a few years of minimal mainte= nance for critical bugs), essentially treating it like an LTS release; afte= r that, no new features, but ensure it compiles/runs on new OS for a while.= We see rudiments of this in how some projects archive their final code and= provide a static site =E2=80=93 that final state is the =E2=80=9CLTS=E2=80= =9D (though without further patches). Backward compatibility is another hallmark of commercia= l practice: e.g., Adobe Photoshop today can still open files created 20+ ye= ars ago, thanks to consistent format support. In research software, backwar= d compatibility often translates to data portability: making sure that data formats remain readable e= ven if the software isn=E2=80=99t the same. The Endings Principles stress t= his by requiring data in standard formatsdh= -tech.github.io =E2=80=93 if a proje= ct=E2=80=99s custom software dies, another tool can potentially read the da= ta. This is essentially a backward compatibility guarantee at the data leve= l, akin to ensuring a Word document from 1995 can be opened in 2025 Word. O= n the software functionality level, backward compatibility in academia is l= ess formal =E2=80=93 but some projects do maintain legacy modes. For exampl= e, the developers of the Pa= ndora text-analysis tool kept older analysis algorithms available = as options even as they overhauled the tool, so that users could reproduce = old results. This mirrors commercial software that retains =E2=80=9Clegacy = mode=E2=80=9D options.

Maintenance and Community Support: In commercial s= ettings, paying for a support contract means someone is on the hook to fix = issues. Academia lacks that straightforward contract model, but it has expe= rimented with community sup= port models, somewhat like open-source communities. Successful res= earch software (e.g., the R statistical environment or the Zotero reference= manager) often transitions from being a grant-funded project to an open-so= urce project supported by a mix of volunteer contributions, institutional b= acking, and sometimes paid staff. Zotero, for instance, started with grants= but is now sustained by George Mason University and an active user communi= ty, plus some revenue streams. The lesson for historical research software = is that if a tool gains a suffi= cient user base (even if small but dedicated), it can leverage community co= ntributions for maintenance. However, many humanities tools never reac= h that critical mass. One promising trend is consortial funding for maintenance: multiple uni= versities or libraries agreeing to jointly fund a developer=E2=80=99s time = to maintain a tool they all use. This echoes commercial consortiums that fu= nd open-source (like companies funding Linux developers because they all re= ly on Linux). The literature cites the example of the Open Journal Systems (OJS) platform =E2= =80=93 initially a research project, now sustained by a consortium of libra= ries because it became infrastructure they depend on (this is mentioned in = some digital preservation discussions as a model).

Finally, the concept of =E2=80=9Csunsetting=E2=80=9D software is handled differently across sectors. Commercial firms carefu= lly manage end-of-life: announcing well in advance, providing migration too= ls or services to move users to a new product. In academia, sunsetting has = often been abrupt (site goes offline, users left stranded). The community i= s learning to do better: for example, when the Digital Antiquity project decided to retire an old arc= haeological tool, they announced it on professional mailing lists, ensured = all data was ported to a newer system (Archaeology Data Service=E2=80=99s r= epository), and even offered workshops for users to transition. This approa= ch =E2=80=93 treating users with the same care as a software company would = treat its customers =E2=80=93 is a best practice highlighted in recent repo= rtsdans.knaw.nl= <= a href=3D"https://dans.knaw.nl/en/news/lcrdm-task-group-publishes-report-re= search-software-sustainability-in-the-netherlands/#:~:text=3DIt%20has%20bee= n%20produced%20in,and%20in%20digital%20competence%20centers" target=3D"_bla= nk" rel=3D"noopener" alt=3D"https://dans.knaw.nl/en/news/lcrdm-task-group-p= ublishes-report-research-software-sustainability-in-the-netherlands/#:~:tex= t=3DIt%20has%20been%20produced%20in,and%20in%20digital%20competence%20cente= rs" class=3D"flex h-4.5 overflow-hidden rounded-xl px-2 text-[9px] font-med= ium transition-colors duration-150 ease-in-out text-token-text-secondary! b= g-[#F4F4F4]! dark:bg-[#303030]!">dans.k= naw.nl. It recognizes that research = software often has an impact beyond its original team, and those stakeholde= rs deserve a say or at least a warning in the software=E2=80=99s lifecycle = events.

In summary, while the context of= academic research software is quite different from commercial software, ma= ny longevity strategies can cross the divide: stable releases, compatibilit= y focus, community funding, clear end-of-life processes. The comparative pe= rspective shows that no sin= gle sector has all the answers, but combining the rigorous mainten= ance culture of industry with the open, community-driven ethos of academia = may yield the most sustainable outcomes for research software.

5. Gaps and Future Directions

Gaps in the Literature: Despite growing attention,= significant gaps remain in our understanding and practice of research soft= ware sustainability, especially in historical studies. One major gap is empirical data on long-term ou= tcomes. We have anecdotes and individual case studies, but there i= s no comprehensive longitudinal study tracking a large sample of historical= research software over, say, 10=E2=80=9320 years. Such data could reveal p= atterns (perhaps certain types of projects last longer, or certain preserva= tion actions correlate with extended lifespan) that currently we can only h= ypothesize. As noted earlier, parallels are drawn from data preservation st= udiesdigitalhumanities.org, but software deserves its own longitu= dinal analysis. Another gap is in metrics and methodologies specific to humanities software. = Frameworks like RSMM provide a generic set of best practices, but they are = not yet tailored to (or validated in) the context of small, interpretative = research projects. It remains an open question how well something like a ma= turity model =E2=80=93 which might require dozens of practices =E2=80=93 ca= n be applied in a resource-constrained humanities lab. There is a need for = lightweight assessment too= ls that account for the realities of these projects. For example, a =E2=80= =9CSustainability Scorecard for Digital History Projects=E2=80=9D could foc= us on a few key predictors (open source, multiple collaborators, archived i= n repository, etc.) and be easier to use than a full maturity model. The li= terature has not yet produced such a tailored tool, representing a methodol= ogical gap.

Another lacuna is qualitative research on user perspectives= . We lack understanding of how end-users of historical software (e= .g. historians using a text mining tool) deal with software obsolescence an= d what they need for continuity. Do they find workarounds? Do they abandon = methods when software breaks? Their perspective could highlight impacts of = sustainability failures (like lost research or reanalysis needed) which cou= ld strengthen the case for investing in sustainability. Similarly, we have = scant information on how often historical researchers reuse software developed by others. If reuse is= low, perhaps because tools are hard to find or hard to learn, that could d= ampen incentives to sustain them. Some evidence suggests reuse is limited in humanities: Barats et al. (2020) hint that unlike = sciences where shared tools (R, Python libraries) are common, humanities pr= ojects often start from scratch or custom-builddigitalhumanities.o= rg. This implies a cultural gap that= future work should address: increasing reuse would naturally improve susta= inability (through network effects and shared maintenance).

Why These Gaps Exist: Several factors contribute t= o these gaps. Historically, digital humanities has been project-focused and= novelty-driven; thus, scholarly reward went to creating new tools or content rather than systematica= lly studying longevity or reuse. Only recently has the community begun to r= eflect on decades of project outcomes =E2=80=93 hence the uptick in sustain= ability discussions around 2018=E2=80=932020ideah.pubpub.org<= /span>. Additionally, measuring software sustainability is inherently trick= y =E2=80=93 software may cease development yet still run (is that =E2=80=9C= sustained=E2=80=9D or not?), or it may evolve into a different project enti= rely. This complexity makes it a less straightforward object of study than,= say, published articles or datasets. However, with the rise of research so= ftware engineering as a recognized field, we now have the expertise and voc= abulary to study these phenomena more rigorously. Another reason is the int= erdisciplinary nature of the problem: it spans computer science (software e= ngineering), information science (digital preservation), and humanities. Br= idging these communities takes time; as of now, literature on this topic is= scattered across venues (some in DH journals, some in software engineering= conferences like WSSSPE, some in library science journals like International Journal of Digital Curation<= /em>). This fragmentation means gaps persisted simply because insights were= n=E2=80=99t being shared across domains. Encouragingly, initiatives like th= e 2020 British Library "Dig= ital Preservation for Humanities Projects" workshop and the ongoin= g Sustainable Digital Herit= age conferences are starting to bring these threads together.

Future Research Directions: To address these gaps,= several directions present themselves. One is comprehensive longitudinal studies: funding ag= encies and consortia could sponsor tracking of a cohort of digital humaniti= es projects over time, with periodic check-ins on their status. This could = be paired with developing i= ndicators of health (akin to how ecologists track species populati= ons). For example, an indicator might be =E2=80=9Cactive installations=E2= =80=9D of a software =E2=80=93 if that number drops to zero, the software i= s effectively dead. Another future direction is developing and validating <= strong data-start=3D"57636" data-end=3D"57668">sustainability interventions= . We have many suggested best practices, but which ones truly make= a difference? For instance, does providing a Docker image actually prolong= the usable life of a tool? Does early involvement of a library in a projec= t significantly improve its preservation outcome? Experimental or quasi-exp= erimental studies (perhaps comparing similar projects with and without cert= ain interventions) could yield evidence-based recommendations, moving beyon= d intuition.

Policy and Structural Changes: Future work should = also explore the policy level. There is increasing advocacy for requiring <= strong data-start=3D"58252" data-end=3D"58288">Software Management Plans (S= MPs) in grant proposals, analogous to Data Management Plansdans.knaw.nldans.knaw.nl<= /span>. A SMP would force project leaders t= o articulate how their software will be documented, licensed, and sustained= or sunset =E2=80=93 even if that means stating that after 3 years it will = be archived in X repository and the live site taken down. The impact of suc= h policies could be significant, but it would be useful to analyze pilot im= plementations. For instance, the EU Horizon Europe program has started to e= mphasize software outputs in their open science policies; studying initial = compliance and outcomes would inform whether this should be scaled up. Addi= tionally, the role of dedicated funding for maintenance (versus only new pr= ojects) is a frontier to push. Some have suggested =E2=80=9Csecond-chance= =E2=80=9D grants for promising digital projects that lack maintenance fundi= ng: essentially, a grant specifically to document, refactor, and archive an= existing tool. Empirical research could identify candidates and measure ho= w effective such interventions are in extending a tool=E2=80=99s life or in= creasing reuse.

Implications for Software Design: The findings fro= m existing literature and anticipated research trends carry important impli= cations for how we design research software from the start. One clear impli= cation is the value of simp= licity and minimalism in design. As the Endings Principles emphasi= ze, every additional layer of technical complexity (a custom database, a fl= ashy JavaScript framework) is another layer that can age and faildh-tech.github.io= ideah.pubpu= b.org. Designing with longevity in m= ind often means choosing simpler, well-supported technologies over cutting-= edge but ephemeral ones. For example, a project might opt for plain text da= ta storage and static site generation rather than a complex relational data= base and dynamic web app, if the former meets the core needs. This isn=E2= =80=99t to stifle innovation but to be deliberate about technical choices i= n light of future maintenance burden. Another implication is to modularize functionality such= that core research data and methods are decoupled from any one interface. = If the visualization front-end of a project becomes obsolete, the data and = analysis modules might be reused in a new interface later. Software archite= cts in research projects should thus emphasize loose coupling and clear API= s, enabling pieces of the project to have independent lives.

Perhaps the most human-centric i= mplication is to document f= or the future stranger. Many studies and reports hammer on documen= tation =E2=80=93 not just user manuals, but technical documentation, data s= chemas, and context. When a project member moves on, their tacit knowledge = often goes with them; good documentation is the surrogate that remains. Fie= lds like software engineering have long known this, but humanities projects= sometimes treated documentation as an afterthought. The literature now is = unequivocal: write documentatio= n as if your project=E2=80=99s future depends on it =E2=80=93 because it li= kely does. Some frameworks (e.g. the Endings Principles and the Nether= lands reportdans.kn= aw.nl) explicitly recommend includin= g documentation in the preserved outputs and even suggest the minimum conte= nts (data dictionary, installation instructions, license info, etc.)dh-tech.github.io.

Community and Training: Finally, future directions= must involve building communities and skills for sustainability. The conce= pt of =E2=80=9CCommunity of= Practice=E2=80=9D for historical software sustainability is emerg= ing =E2=80=93 bringing together digital historians, librarians, and RSEs to= share successes and failures. Knowledge exchange platforms (like the DHTec= h forum or the RSE-HPC-CH group in Switzerland) help disseminate these less= ons so each project doesn=E2=80=99t start from scratch on sustainability pl= anning. Training programs too will play a role. Just as graduate students a= re now taught data management, they should be introduced to basic software = sustainability concepts if they engage in digital projects: how to use vers= ion control, why to choose an open license, how to prepare a project for ha= nd-off. Such cultural shifts will take time but are underway through organi= zations like The Carpentries (which has modules on version control and open= science that are equally applicable to historians coding).

In conclusion, bridging the gaps= will require coordinated efforts on multiple fronts =E2=80=93 research, po= licy, design, and education. The literature provides a solid foundation and= many cautionary tales; the next step is turning those into action and stud= ying the outcomes, thereby creating a virtuous cycle of improvement in the = longevity of research software.

Future-Proofing and Actionable Insights: Based on= this review, some actionable insights for practitioners and project leader= s in historical studies are: (1) Plan for Preservation from Day 1 =E2=80=93 adopt a sustainab= ility framework (be it FAIR, Endings, or a simple checklist) at project sta= rt and update it throughout the project. (2) Document and Deposit =E2=80=93 ensure all softwa= re and data have thorough documentation and are deposited in trustworthy re= positories with persistent identifiers by project end<= span class=3D"relative start-0 bottom-0 flex h-full w-full items-center">ideah.pubpub.orgideah.pubpub.org. (3) Embrace Open Source and Community= =E2=80=93 open-sourcing your code (with a proper license) and eng= aging potential users beyond your team can significantly extend its life th= rough collective maintenancearxiv.orgarxiv.org. (4) Design for Exit<= /strong> =E2=80=93 design software so that if tomorrow your funding stopped= , the scholarly content (data, results) would remain accessible (via static= pages or archived files)ideah.pubpub.orgideah.pubpub.org<= /span>. (5) Advocate for Support =E2=80=93 include sustainability in the co= nversation with funders and institutions; argue for the value of maintainin= g digital scholarship as part of the scholarly record, much like preserving= books and articles. These steps, drawn from the literature, can help move = the community from simply lamenting lost projects to actively ensuring that= today=E2=80=99s tools and resources will be available to future scholars.<= /p>

FAIR for Research Software (FAI= R4RS Principles) =E2=80=93 RDA/Force11 (2022)

A major international effort, le= d by the Research Data Alliance (RDA), Force11, and the Research Software A= lliance (ReSA), culminated in 2022 with the publication of the FAIR Principles for Research Software (FAIR4RS)researchsoft.org. These principles are an adaptation of the original FAIR data pr= inciples, tailored to the nuances of software. Key aspects include:

  • Findable: Software (and its component modules) sho= uld be easy to find by humans and machines. This involves clear naming, ind= exing in searchable repositories, and use of unique identifiers. For softwa= re, versioning is critical =E2=80=93 so the principles stress the importanc= e of indexing all versions= of software with persistent IDsdoi.org.

  • Accessible: It should be clear how to access the s= oftware, whether through download of source code, installation of a package= , or access to an executable service. Even if software cannot be open-sourc= e (for legal or security reasons), metadata describing how to obtain it sho= uld be open.

  • Interoperable: Software should use open, documente= d formats and APIs, and ideally be built on open-source dependencies, to ma= ximize its ability to work with other tools and platforms.

  • Reusable: Software should be documented, licensed = for reuse, and include metadata on provenance (e.g. who built it, for what = purpose) so that others can judge whether it is appropriate for their needs= . Reusability also ties to = credit =E2=80=93 the principles encourage proper citation of softw= are, so authors get recognitiongoingdigital.oecd.org.

The FAIR4RS principles were publ= ished as an RDA Recommendation with a DOIresearchsoft.org and simultaneously as a paper in Scientific Data (Nature) in 2022 (= Chue Hong et al.). They pr= ovide a common framework now being adopted by journals, repositories, and funders to evaluate= and improve the handling of software in the scholarly ecosystemresearchsoft.org. For example, some data repositories expanded to accept softwar= e submissions, and the principles have been endorsed in the context of the = EOSC and national open science policies.

  • When importing into Zotero, you = may wish to adjust the item types (e.g., =E2=80=9CReport,=E2=80=9D =E2=80= =9CDocument,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWebpage,=E2=80=9D etc.) and re-check author = fields.

  • For large committees and governm= ent bodies, I have listed them as the =E2=80=9Cauthor=E2=80=9D to comply wi= th the request not to use =E2=80=9Cet al.=E2=80=9D and to maintain consiste= ncy.

These BibTeX entries should be valid for most reference manag= ers, including Zotero. Feel free to modify or add details (e.g., publicatio= n month, publisher location) if you have additional metadata.
